On Fri, 19 Sep 2003 08:22:59 +0100, &quot;Chris Dollin&quot; &lt;chris.dollin@...&gt;
said:
&gt; 
&gt;     assertTrue( informative message, boolean )
&gt; 
&gt; It is a deep shame that Java doesn&#39;t have method literals (aka lambdas,
&gt; or Smalltalk blocks, or whatever) so that `informative message` could be
&gt; a hairy expression that&#39;s not actually evaluated unless the test fails.

How about this? :)

public abstract class HairyExpression {
    /**
      * evaluates a hairy expression and returns a message
      * based on the evaluation
      */
    public abstract String evaluate();

    public String toString() {
        return evaluate();
    }
}

assertTrue(
    new HairyExpression () {
        public String evaluate() {
            ...
        }},
    false);

Then extend the Assert capabilities of JUnit to use the toString() of the
object passed in if the assertion fails.

There are of course better ways of doing these things.  I just wanted to
make the point that we can make the framework do anything we want.  Is it
pretty?  No.  But if it&#39;s necessary who cares if it&#39;s pretty (he says
tongue-in-cheek)?

